: BUILDING OF NATIONAL GEM AND JEWELLERY AUTHORITY
AT GALLE FACE TERRACE: COURT CASE 616/2025 6.
() , ? asked the Minister of Industry and Entrepreneurship Development:
(i) there is a building and a land belonging to the National Gem and Jewellery Authority located at Galle Face Terrace, Kollupitiya;
(ii) the building concerned has now subsided due to the impact of the construction of a new building by Renuka Holdings on the land adjacent to it; and
(iii) a case has been filed by the Authority against Renuka Holdings in this regard?

(b) Will he inform this House whether it has been planned to settle the case and sell the relevant building and the land to Renuka Holdings in accordance with a decision of the Board of Directors appointed by the present Government?

MATERNITY AND CHILDRENS HOSPITAL, NAGODA: STAFF
() , ? asked the Minister of Health and Mass Media:
(a) Will he inform this House - (i) whether medical officers, nurses, minor staff and non-academic staff are available in adequate numbers at the Maternity and Childrens Hospital in Gallassa, Nagoda;

The conduct of His Majesty, Members of the Royal Family, the Governor or Officer Administering the Government, Members of either House of Parliament, Judges or other persons engaged in the administration of justice shall not be raised except upon a substantive motion.
....... - I say very grave allegations - against the conduct of a magistrate which were quite improper and out of Order under Section 89 of our Standing Orders.
"I am merely saying that because we must carry on the proceedings of this House according to the Standing Orders."

I wish to refer to the submission made by the Hon. Prime Minister yesterday that the remarks made in the course of a discussion on the 18th August, 1958, on a motion by the First Member for Colombo Central (Mr. Keuneman) for a cut in the salary of the Magistrate, Kegalle were in contravention of the provisions of Standing Order 89. Standing Order 89 reads as follows:
"The discussion on the motion was directed at the conduct of the magistrate concerned in relation to the administration of justice in his court,..."
He says that it had nothing to do with his personal conduct, but with regard "to the administration of justice in his court". Then, he continues,
...and as such I am of opinion that the discussion was out of order. I regret that this irregularity has occurred.

Quite apart from that I have to bring to your notice one more matter. In your speech you referred to the conduct of a Magistrate. That is prevented by the rules of debate in this House. I will have to expunge all those references.
It can appear in a newspaper, you can quote it or you can say it out of your own volition, but if it contravenes rules of debate, if it refers to the conduct of a Magistrate, it has to be expunged.
